<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Wins Support for EU Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Wins Support for EU Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506105994 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1000 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government has won a vote of confidence from the 
Eduskunta on its policy aimed at obtaining membership in the 
European Union [EU]. The Eduskunta rejected the proposal by the 
Leftist Alliance of a vote of no confidence by 97 votes to 80. 
Sixteen representatives of the government parties abstained: 
nine from the Center Party, six from the Christian League, and 
one from the Swedish People's Party. The National Coalition 
Party unanimously supported the government. No representative of 
the government parties voted against the government. Of the 
opposition parties, one representative of the Greens and the 
sole representative of the Liberal Party supported the 
government. 
  Prime Minister Esko Aho interpreted the vote as meaning that 
there are no obstacles for the government to pursue its EU line. 
However, each government party must define its own stance on the 
matter. According to Aho, it was good that the results of the 
vote of confidence were clear. What was not so good was that 
the support from the government parties was not unanimous. 
  According to Foreign Trade Minister Pertti Salolainen, the 
Eduskunta's decision will calm the financial markets. 

</TEXT>

