<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister `Satisfied' With UN Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister `Satisfied' With UN Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1506074094 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0430 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1506074094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis concluded the 
first round of his talks in New York and today will go to 
Washington for talks with U.S. Government and Senate officials. 
Mikhailidhis will meet U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe 
Talbott; U.S. presidential adviser George Stephanopoulos; 
Claiborne Pell, the chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations 
Committee; and Senator Paul Sarbanes. 
  In New York the foreign minister had meetings with the 
representatives of all the UN Security Council members except 
U.S. Ambassador Madeleine Albright, who was not in New York. He 
also had a working luncheon with UN official Marrack Goulding. 
  In a statement to the Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation 
correspondent in New York, Mikhailidhis said he was satisfied 
with his talks, adding that the Security Council members see the 
need for a new opening. He mentioned that he is starting to be 
optimistic that continuous involvement by the Security Council, 
either the entire council or just the permanent members, in 
efforts to find ways to change the basic problem--the lack of 
goodwill by the Turkish side--is an idea that is becoming more 
acceptable. 
  Referring to the talks between Gustave Feissel, the UN 
secretary general's deputy special representative in Cyprus, and 
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas, Mikhailidhis said it is 
important whether Denktas has accepted the 21 March UN document 
in its entirety, not if he has accepted one or the other 
provision. 
  In his statement, the foreign minister said that all 
indications show that UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali's 
communication with the Security Council about the talks between 
Denktas and Feissel will be based on the report that Feissel 
will submit to him. Mikhailidhis said this report is expected in 
New York soon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

