<H3> <TI>   Previti: Troops `Ready To Leave for Rwanda' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Previti: Troops `Ready To Leave for Rwanda' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1306132994 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1517 GMT 10 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1306132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Rwanda: Italian Forces Ready, </F>
Defence Minister Say"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Taranto, June 10 -- Italian troops are ready 
to leave for Rwanda, "as on other occasions," if the situation 
is clarified internationally and a programme for a peace 
intervention is drawn up, Italian Defence Minister Cesare 
Previti pledged here today. 
  Speaking at ceremonies and events for Navy Day, he said the 
UN had so far not approached Italy on the timing or modalities 
of an Italian contribution. "The only request we have received 
so far is for a C-130 transport plane, which we sent at once," 
he reported. 
  According to Previti, Foreign Minister Antonio Martino is 
pursuing policies whereby there will be a greater Italian 
involvement in peace operations. "Naturally," he added, "they 
could never be unilateral or fail to take account of the 
international context in which they are being promoted." 
  Previti also recalled that, at the Group of Seven summit in 
Naples, Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi will be proposing a UN 
task force for humanitarian missions such as those needed in 
situations such as Rwanda's. 
  "The idea is to rationalise the possible forms of 
humanitarian intervention the world can make in the most 
tortured situations of war and calamity," he asserted. 
  In other points, in his official speech and a later press 
conference, Previti said he would be trying to reverse the past 
trend towards defence cuts, saying the objective remains to 
modernise and re-shape the armed forces on the principle of 
"more quality, less quantity." 
  "The Cold War is over," he said, adding that the use of the 
Italian armed forces must now be only a "function of the 
country's international presence." 
  Previti also said military service would be reduced in 
favour 
of an increase in the number of volunteer servicemen. 

</TEXT>

