<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel: EU Entry for East Europe Not Certain by 2000 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel: EU Entry for East Europe Not Certain by 2000 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506174494 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU in German 
15 Jun 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU1506174494 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Erich Hauser: "Kinkel Appeals for Patience"] </F>
  [Text] Luxembourg, 14 July -- It might not necessarily be 
possible for the Central and East European countries to join the 
European Union [EU] by the year 2000. With this statement, 
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel at a news conference in Luxembourg 
warned the governments in Prague, Warsaw, Bratislava, Budapest, 
Bucharest, and Sofia, which have associate membership agreements 
with the European Union, against too high expectations from 
Bonn's imminent EU presidency. Nevertheless, the Federal 
Government will do everything to lead the six associated 
partners "closer to the European Union," and knows that Paris 
and Madrid, which will take over the EU presidency in the first 
and second six months of 1995, respectively, will do the same, 
Kinkel said. 
  As far as the plans for nominating a successor to EU 
Commission President Jacques Delors are concerned, Bonn and 
Paris will "not ignore the opinion of the smaller member 
states." The fact that he will not comment on the plans of the 
two governments to nominate the Belgian Jean-Luc Dehaene at the 
upcoming EU summit on Corfu can be interpreted as "meaningful 
silence," Kinkel added cryptically. 
  At the summit meeting at the end of next week, one will also 
have to clarify whether two representatives of the Parliament of 
Europe and the governments of Austria and the three Scandinavian 
EU membership candidates will be involved in a "preparatory 
group" for the revision of the Maastricht Treaty, the minister 
said. Only Germany, Spain, Belgium, and the Netherlands have so 
far come out in favor of the participation of the Parliament. 
According to the four membership treaties, which will be signed 
on Corfu in a ceremony, the candidate countries will be entitled 
to participate in all EU Council sessions and in the EU 
Ambassadors' Committee with a "seat and vote." 
  Italy has raised objections in the EU Council of Ministers 
against preparing an EU associate membership agreement with 
Slovenia. Rome and Ljubljana must first settle compensation 
claims of Italian "expellees." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-43357 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu116_b_94002" </HT>


