<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Stable Relations in Luxembourg -- </F>
No Surprises at the Elections"] 
  [Text] The "Hei Elei" [Luxembourg Television] factor 
unintentionally produced an exciting election yesterday. 
  According to initial projections that were circulated in the 
early afternoon, the LSAP [Socialist Workers' Party of 
Luxembourg] was to suffer a crushing defeat and the DP 
[Democratic Party] was to record a landslide gain. 
  The sober verdict of the electorate was quite different. 
Both the CSV [Christian Social People's Party] and the LSAP 
suffered slight losses throughout the country, which cost the 
two governing parties one seat each, but the Liberals did not 
achieve the breakthrough they had hoped for--they merely 
consolidated their 12th seat, which Josy Simon's defection had 
already secured for them a year ago. 
  The "Greens" turned gray out of sheer disappointment when 
they received only five instead of the 10 to 11 seats they had 
hoped for. 
  The Communist Party and New Left were cast into the 
political 
wilderness where they join the National Movement. The ADR 
[Action Committee for Democracy and Pension Fairness], with its 
populist pension claims, achieved a reasonable success which the 
next government ought to build on in order to deal with this 
important question of basic justice. 
  Otherwise, it was a quiet election day in Luxembourg, one 
which caused the international agencies, in view of the 
perceived stability, to forecast a continuation of the present 
coalition. We must wait and see. 
