<H3> <TI>   SPD Considers Cooperation With PDS </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPD Considers Cooperation With PDS </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506161194 Berlin DIE WELT in German 15 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1506161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by "DW": "Controversial Cooperation"] </F>
  [Text] Berlin -- After the municipal elections in four new 
laender, the Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD] is partly 
prepared for cooperation with the Party of Democratic Socialism 
[PDS]. Yesterday, SPD Deputy Chairman Wolfgang Thierse no 
longer ruled out such a cooperation for his party in eastern 
German municipalities. The PDS representatives must not be 
treated like lepers and thus turned into martyrs, he said. All 
parties are obliged to cooperate in order to solve the pending 
problems. This is something completely different from 
coalitions with the PDS on the land and federal level, which he 
considers impossible. 
  First offers have already been made by the successor party 
of 
the Socialist Unity Party of Germany. For example, Wolfgang 
Methling, PDS frontrunner in Rostock, stated that the PDS does 
not want "to govern the city at all costs." Methling announced 
coalition talks with the Alliance 90/Greens and the SPD. 
According to the preliminary result, in the Hanseatic city the 
PDS gains 20 seats, the SPD 16, the CDU 11, and the Greens six. 
  In Thuringia, however, the SPD has basically opposed 
coalitions with the PDS. Last evening, the land executive 
committee of the party still wanted to discuss a recommendation 
to the district and local associations not to form any 
coalitions with the PDS on a local level. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

