<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   PDS Maintains Contacts With `Extreme-Left' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PDS Maintains Contacts With `Extreme-Left' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506195294 Berlin DIE WELT in German 15 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1506195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Peter Scherer: "PDS -- `Test Case' for the </F>
Office for the Protection of the Constitution"] 
  [Text] Frankfurt/Main -- According to the assessment of 
the Office for the Protection of the Constitution, "extreme-left 
positions" are being taken in the successor party of the 
Socialist Unity Party of Germany and the Party of Democratic 
Socialism [PDS], and "lively contacts" with 
revolutionary-Marxist organizations are being maintained. This 
particularly applies to the "Communist Platform" (KPF), which 
was founded within the PDS with its explicit approval and whose 
activists openly declare themselves in favor of the 
"revolutionary idea of the socialist alternative." According to 
the Office for the Protection of the Constitution, the 
Marxist-Leninist KPF regards itself as a bridge to other 
communist groups and it maintains close and regular contacts, 
particularly with the German Communist Party [DKP] and the 
Communist Party of Germany [KPD]. Thus, this association has to 
be assessed as a "test case" for the Office for the Protection 
of the Constitution. 
  In an interview with the DKP newspaper UNSERE ZEIT, PDS 
Chairman Lothar Bisky explains the PDS view on cooperation with 
communists in the election campaigns as follows: "A decision 
that communists are not to be put on PDS lists has not been 
made. I would also regard it as a loss." 
  According to the Office for the Protection of the 
Constitution, the PDS is also not "afraid of coming into 
contact" with violent extremists. As proof, the 1993 report of 
the Office for the Protection of the Constitution quotes from 
the 17th edition of the PDS member magazine DISPUT, which says, 
among other things, the following: "The PDS has a good position 
in the scientific analysis of the fascist development. 
Consistently, however, it will have to bank far more on 
extraparliamentary actions and self-help. It would be stupid to 
leave autonomous groups alone in actions that would be worth 
supporting, for example, if the `concrete prevention of Nazi 
meetings' is at issue." PDS members also participated in a 
congress of leftist groups in Hamburg to which members of the 
terrorist scene had also come. 
  According to the Office for the Protection of the 
Constitution, PDS members also participated in the 
"Socialist-Communist Action Unit," which is operated by the KPD 
and whose objective is the founding of a "uniform Communist 
Party of Germany." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

