<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paris Welcomes Rwanda Cease-Fire, Condemns Massacre </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paris Welcomes Rwanda Cease-Fire, Condemns Massacre </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506150794 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1400 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The cease-fire agreement for Rwanda was formally 
announced a moment ago during the closing ceremony of the OAU 
summit in Tunis. The agreement envisions dialogue and 
negotiation as the means to settle the conflict between the 
[Rwandan] Patriotic Front and the interim government. It should 
have taken effect immediately yesterday evening, but it appears 
that the fighting is continuing in Kigali. 
  Paris has taken note of this latest cease-fire agreement and 
expressed satisfaction with it, but the French Government 
condemned the massacre which took place in a church in the 
Rwandan capital, Kigali, which is reported to have resulted in 
30-40 deaths, according to the United Nations. 

</TEXT>

