<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kliridhis To Give Reasons for Resignation Threat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kliridhis To Give Reasons for Resignation Threat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1606111194 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1606111194 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Glavkos Kliridhis has said that within the 
next few days he will give the reasons that led him to tell U.S. 
President Bill Clinton and British Prime Minister John Major 
that he may resign and declare early elections if the UN 
Security Council decides to continue the negotiations on the 
confidence-building measures. 
  In a statement after a ceremony to receive the credentials 
of 
the new Portuguese ambassador, Kliridhis mentioned that he 
expects Clinton and Major to reply to his letter. He added that 
he has some indications of the way the two leaders will react. 
  Commenting on the resolution that the UN Security Council 
adopted yesterday to renew the UNFICYP [UN Forces in Cyprus] 
mandate, the president noted that the resolution sends out the 
correct messages because it stresses the need to implement the 
confidence-building measures, not to continue the talks on them. 
He added it is important that a new, detailed revision of the 
Cyprus issue be made according to yesterday's resolution, and 
that all of the alternatives that are listed in the UN secretary 
general's report be examined. The president said he does not 
rule out that Butrus-Ghali's options will be simultaneously 
studied with the confidence-building measures procedure if 
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas accepts the 21 March UN 
document. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-43405 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu116_o_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-116 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Lists `Hypothetical Scenarios' on Future </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Lists `Hypothetical Scenarios' on Future </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1506130394 Nicosia ELEVTHEROTIPIA in Greek 15 Jun 94 pp 1, 
6 </F>

<F P=103> NC1506130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia ELEVTHEROTIPIA </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] President Glavkos Kliridhis yesterday confirmed 
reports that he intends to resign if the Security Council 
decides to continue the current procedure on the 
confidence-building measures, despite the UN secretary general's 
clear evaluation that the Turkish side has no political will for 
a solution. [passage omitted] 
  Political observers yesterday interpreted Kliridhis' open 
warning as an answer to insistent efforts at the Security 
Council and in Cyprus -- with the continuous meetings between 
Gustave Feissel, the UN secretary general's alternate special 
representative in Cyprus, and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf 
Denktas -- to help the Turkish Cypriot side, even though the 
"agreement" on the 21 March document is set. 
  It must be noted that there has been no reply so far to 
Kliridhis' letters to U.S. President Bill Clinton and British 
Prime Minister John Major. 
  Asked to explain the reasons that may force Kliridhis to 
resign, Government Spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis clarified that 
this is a strictly personal issue for the president and noted 
the "inconsistency" of others, implying the United States and 
Britain. 
  Kasoulidhis mentioned that there are three hypothetical 
scenarios: a) Denktas accepts the 21 March UN document, and 
there is an agreement on the confidence-building measures; b) 
negotiations begin on issues other than the 21 March document; 
c) a dialogue begins and our side raises its objections. 
  Kasoulidhis said that in the first case we would have 
immediate agreement. The National Council's decision, to which 
the president is committed, clearly states that discussion on 
the confidence-building measures has ended. However, the 
president made it clear to National Council members that he has 
accepted the 21 March UN document, and if Denktas accepts it, 
even now, he will accept it too. 
  A serious issue would be created if talks begin on issues 
other than the 21 March UN document, because the UN secretary 
general's representatives told the president it was the last UN 
document. As a result, Kliridhis lifted his objections to reach 
an agreement. 
  In the third case, Kasoulidhis said reservations and 
objections would return to the negotiating table if we were led 
to an endless procedure. He added: Although we will also raise 
objections, our side will be in a very difficult position 
because the president has accepted the 21 March document. 
  The spokesman stressed that the president believes that, if 
necessary, he would make it easier for the Cypriot Hellenism to 
call for presidential elections in order for the new president 
to receive a public order without the obligation of accepting 
the document. 
  Commenting on an observation that Denktas may finally give a 
positive answer, the spokesman said: "Denktas supposedly has 
approached some UN positions, but not the 21 March document." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

