<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Criticizes Greek Cypriots </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Criticizes Greek Cypriots </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1506172394 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1430 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1506172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara (AA) -- Foreign Ministry spokesman Ferhat 
Ataman has said that the stand adopted by the Greek Cypriot side 
demonstrates its intransigent intentions and approach to the 
confidence-building measures [CBM] process and to efforts aimed 
at finding a solution through negotiations. 
  In reply to a question on the issue at his weekly news 
conference today, Ataman recalled Greek Cypriot claims that the 
CBM process has been terminated. 
  Pointing out that the positive and constructive approach 
adopted by the Turkish Cypriot side has created an atmosphere of 
restlessness and uneasiness in south Cyprus, Ataman noted that 
the Greek Cypriot National Council has unanimously declared that 
it is out of the question to return to the CBM process. 
  Ataman recalled Greek Foreign Minister Papoulias' statement 
in Istanbul that the CBM process is dead, adding that, however, 
the British foreign minister and the U.S. secretary of state 
made statements conveying that the process is continuing. 
  Ataman continued: 
  For some time now there have been reports in the Greek 
Cypriot press that the successful attitude of the Turkish 
Cypriot side is causing concern and that if the process 
continues the Greek Cypriot side will not hesitate to take a 
stand against the United Nations. Greek Cypriot leader 
Kliridhis' threat to resign has also been interpreted by the 
Greek Cypriot press as a form of blackmail against the United 
Nations. 
  As you can understand this interpretation shows that the 
stand adopted by the Greek Cypriot side demonstrates its 
intransigent intentions and approach to the CBM process and to 
efforts aimed at finding a solution to the Cyprus problem 
through negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

