<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arsenis To Visit U.S.; Comments on Aegean Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arsenis To Visit U.S.; Comments on Aegean Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1506183494 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1700 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1506183494 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] National Defense Minister Yerasimos Arsenis will 
discuss with his U.S. counterpart defense aspects of Greek-U.S. 
relations and the question of air navigation in the Aegean which 
was the subject of recent remarks by the U.S. Secretary of 
State. Mr. Arsenis will begin a visit to the United States on 
Sunday [19 June] to attend an informal NATO conference. 
  The national defense minister stressed in a statement that 
Greek fighter aircraft, according to NATO regulations, must be 
armed if they intercept unidentified aircraft that violate the 
rules of air traffic in the Athens FIR [Flight Information 
Region] or violate national airspace. 
  On the subject of Mr. Warren Christopher's statement, the 
national defense minister said that anyone who wants the 
artificial tension that was recently created between Greece and 
Turkey to be defused should see who is doing the violations and 
infringements. 
  The national defense minister referred to the Turkish 
maneuvers Sea Wolf and Efes-94, which are being held in the 
eastern Aegean, as well as the efforts by the Turkish press 
because of these maneuvers to depict Greek-Turkish relations as 
tense, and he pointed out that these maneuvers were scheduled 
some time ago and, as is natural, they are being followed by our 
country as Turkey also follows the Greek maneuvers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

