<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Regrets PRC Nuclear Experiment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Regrets PRC Nuclear Experiment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1506185294 Ankara ANATOLIA in Turkish 1630 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1506185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Ministry Spokesman Ferhat Ataman has 
expressed regret over the nuclear experiments being conducted by 
the PRC when work on a treaty banning nuclear experiments is 
gaining momentum. 
  Speaking at a news conference today, Ataman expressed 
Turkey's belief that it is necessary to sign a comprehensive 
international treaty banning nuclear experiments, which have 
many environmental, health, and security drawbacks from the 
viewpoint of the future of humanity. 
  Ataman said: 
  We regret to learn that the PRC has, in the last few days, 
conducted another nuclear experiment when work on a treaty 
banning nuclear experiments is gaining momentum and when 
countries with nuclear capabilities are taking steps to make 
their unilateral decisions to halt these experiments permanent. 
  Turkey believes in the necessity of signing a comprehensive 
international treaty -- which will be a significant 
complementary factor in helping the Nuclear Nonproliferation 
Treaty attain its goals -- banning nuclear experiments, which 
have many environmental, health, and security drawbacks from the 
viewpoint of the future of humanity. Turkey further notes that 
it is doing all it can on the issue and finds it beneficial to 
stress that it is deeply concerned and displeased about any kind 
of behavior that might endanger the promising work being 
accomplished on this path. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

