<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-117 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN's Efforts on Confidence-Building Measures Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN's Efforts on Confidence-Building Measures Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Denktas, Feissel View Talks </H4>

<F P=102> NC1606194894 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1400 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1606194894 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rauf Denktas, in a new maneuver, appears in a 
statement to have accepted all the points raised by the United 
Nations on the confidence-building measures. Speaking to 
correspondents after his meeting with Gustave Feissel today, 
Denktas said that Mr. Feissel must be satisfied now because he 
said that he gave Feissel all that he wanted. He further 
maintained that Feissel also gave the Turkish Cypriot side what 
it wanted. Denktas said that some changes will be made to the 
latest UN document of 21 March. He also noted that what is left 
now is to prepare the draft agreement for signing. 
  Gustave Feissel said after the meeting that Rauf Denktas has 
moved from some of his positions, but it has not become clear 
whether he accepts the 21 March UN document as is. Despite 
repeated questions from journalists, Mr. Feissel avoided saying 
whether the document had been accepted. He said: It is up to 
the UN secretary general and the Security Council to decide 
whether the clarifications given by Denktas today represent a 
development in the right direction. 
  Feissel confirmed that Denktas did not give anything in 
writing and added that today's meeting with him was the last. 
  The UN secretary general's representative has briefed 
President Glavkos Kliridhis on Denktas' clarifications. 
  In a statement made to CyBC [Cyprus Broadcasting 
Corporation] 
a short time ago, Gustave Feissel noted that what Rauf Denktas 
said about him having accepted all the points on the 
confidence-building measures is only the opinion of the Turkish 
Cypriot leader. Asked if Mr. Feissel really gave all that 
Denktas was demanding, as the Turkish Cypriot leader had said, 
according to REUTER, the UN official replied that this was 
inaccurate. Mr. Feissel made it clear that his mission was not 
to agree on anything. He added: My mission was to receive some 
clarifications, which I did and I will convey them to New York. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

