<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demirel Praises Army Readiness, Comments on Cyprus </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Demirel Praises Army Readiness, Comments on Cyprus </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1606151894 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1430 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1606151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On board Turkish frigate Fatih, June 16 (A.A.) -- 
President Suleyman Demirel said that the Turkish Armed Forces 
was ready to fulfill any duty assigned to itself. 
  On board the frigate Fatih during the Sea Wolf-94 exercise, 
Demirel said that a forcible solution on Cyprus would lead to 
turbulences on the island and would also reopen deep wounds 
between Turkey and Greece. 
  After the conclusion of the exercise, Demirel told a press 
conference that the Turkish nation felt great security because 
of its strong army. 
  `Our Armed Forces will fulfill any duty given to it by the 
people and the state,' Demirel said. `Both exercises were 
carried out excellently. Everyone can easily notice the great 
discipline and high-level of training the Army members have.' 
  Answering a question about Cyprus, Demirel said that peace 
was established on the island ever since the 1974 Peace 
Operation in Turkey. 
  `However,' he added, `a solution has been sought since then. 
A conclusion was not reached yet on a bi-zonal, bi-communal 
federated state based on political equality.' 
  `In fact,' he added, `the actual situation on the island is 
a 
solution. It has ended the bloodshed and the fighting between 
the two communities.' 
  He also stressed that the Greek Cypriot Administration in 
the 
south was recognized by the world as the Republic of Cyprus 
while the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus [TRNC] was 
recognized only by Turkey. 
  `The 150,000 Turks in Cyprus are being treated by the world 
as if they were in a hostage camp in the eastern part of the 
Mediterranean,' he said. 
  Demirel went on to say that the world was still hostile 
against the Turkish presence in northern Cyprus. 
  `The per capita income in south Cyprus is 10,000 U.S. 
dollars 
while this figure is 3,000 dollars in the TRNC,' he said. 
  `It is necessary to seek a viable solution in Cyprus, rather 
than trying to impose a non-operative one,' he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

