<H3> <TI>   Italy Improves Record on Adopting EU Laws </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Italy Improves Record on Adopting EU Laws </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1606141894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1252 GMT 16 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1606141894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Italy Improves Record on Adopting </F>
European Union Laws"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Luxembourg, June 6 -- Italy has greatly 
improved its record of adopting European Union [EU] laws and 
regulations and, with an adoption rate of 89.9 percent, now 
ranks fourth among the Member States for turning European Union 
into national law, according to the executive European 
Commissioner for the Single Market, Italy's Raniero Vanni 
d'Archirafi. 
  Denmark ranked first for adopting European Union law for 
having made its own 96 percent of European legislature, followed 
by Portugal with a 91 percent rate, the Netherlands at 90 
percent and then Italy. 
  Observers pointed out how Denmark and Portugal, with 
sixth-ranked Britain, were considered the greatest 
"Euro-skeptics," while Germany, viewed as the locomotive for 
European integration was third to last in adopting European 
Union laws, at a rate of 83 percent, while France stood at 87 
percent, fourth-to-last. 
  In an address to ministers responsible for European affairs, 
for Italy Domenico Comino, Vanni d'Archirafi announced how the 
European Commission had decided to "go on the warpath" to speed 
up the transformation of European Union law into national law. 
The EU executive, he said, was considering adopting, from now 
on, penalties and sanctions for the delays, as provided for in 
the Maastricht Treaty on European Union. 

</TEXT>

