<H3> <TI>   Treasury Minister: Ruling on Pensions `Bad News' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Treasury Minister: Ruling on Pensions `Bad News' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1306133594 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1959 GMT 12 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1306133594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Dini on Court Ruling on Pensions, </F>
Spending"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Washington, June 12 -- Saturday's [11 June] 
ruling by Italy's constitutional court restoring pension 
minimums to as many as 600,000 retired persons for an estimated 
cost to the social security system of up to 16 trillion lire is 
"bad news" for the Treasury, said Minister Lamberto Dini. 
  The top treasury official spoke in an interview with ANSA 
during a visit here to meet U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd 
Bentsen and Director General of the International Monetary Fund 
Michel Camdessus. 
  Dini called the decision "a potential element worsening the 
public accounts balance that the government will have to take 
note of during the preparation of the 1995 budget." 
  The Treasury Minister did not rule out the need for new 
budget adjustments soon to counteract the spending increase that 
ruling will entail. 
  Dini said his U.S. and IMF interlocutors, with whom he 
talked 
about topics that will be discussed during the July Group of 
Seven summit in Naples, had shown great interest in the 1995 
budget, "from which they expect to be able to evaluate the 
economic policy and strategy of the government." 

</TEXT>

