<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visit by Italian Prime Minister Berlusconi Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Visit by Italian Prime Minister Berlusconi Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Berlusconi Proposes Human Rights Task Force </H4>

<F P=102> LD1606115694 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 1100 
GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1606115694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Italian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Just after he arrived in Bonn, his first visit 
abroad, Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi submitted a proposal: 
Italy wants to create an autonomous task force to defend human 
rights against suffering. But Prime Minister Berlusconi's visit 
has also given rise to controversy from the German Left on the 
presence of neofascist ministers in the Italian Government. 
Giovanni Masotti, our correspondent, reports from Bonn: 
  [Masotti] Silvio Berlusconi is making his first visit 
abroad, 
to Bonn, and the prime minister is again under pressure over the 
delicate matter of National Alliance ministers in the 
government. The controversy has been reopened by the German 
Social Democrats who are in serious difficulty following their 
defeat in the European elections and by the Greens. The 
left-wing opposition is asking Chancellor Kohl both to distance 
himself from Berlusconi and to stop Forza Italia from joining 
the European People's Party in the European Parliament. The 
accusation of having opened the door of government to the 
neofascists is rejected by the prime minister in an interview 
published today in the Bonn daily newspaper GENERALE ANZEIGER. 
Berlusconi says that the National Alliance party fully accepts 
and respects the Italian Constitution and the laws of the 
democratic state. It has nothing to do with Le Pen or the 
German extreme right-wing. The first goal that my government 
has set itself, Berlusconi stresses, is that of realizing and 
respecting the state of law. A press conference will be held in 
the afternoon by the prime minister. He will then immediately 
leave for Rome. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

