<H3> <TI>   WEU Secretary General on Intervention in Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    WEU Secretary General on Intervention in Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706175494 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1700 
GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706175494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] It is no secret that European and African states are 
rather reluctant to intervene in Rwanda. Today, Paris has 
multiplied its efforts to persuade them by stressing the purely 
humanitarian aspect of the operation. In Brussels the Western 
European Union [WEU] has been considering French proposals. WEU 
Secretary General Willem van Eekelen explains: 
  [Begin van Eekelen recording] Everyone agrees that the 
situation in Rwanda is tragic and that we must see if European 
countries can do something. The WEU will now consider how it 
could coordinate extra contributions from European countries 
under the aegis of the United Nations. Our planning cell has 
been allowed to get in touch with capitals to see which 
capabilities, which means, could be placed at our disposal and 
closely to follow developments. This is a start, and now a 
possible scenario must be assessed, we must then see which 
countries will be able to contribute. [end recording] 

