<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Minister Urges Reduction in EU Commission Powers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    French Minister Urges Reduction in EU Commission Powers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1606152494 Paris LE MONDE in French 16 Jun 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> BR1606152494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE MONDE </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Ph. L." report: "Alain Lamassoure Calls For Reduction of </F>
European Commission Powers"] 
  [Text] An aftershock of the European election? An 
acknowledgement of the supposed hostility of some 23 percent of 
right-wing and extreme-right-wing French voters (those who chose 
the de Villiers and Le Pen lists) toward "Brussels' 
technocrats?" In any case, since recently, French officials 
have appeared rather forceful in their determination to take 
advantage of the 1996 intergovernmental conference on EU 
political and institutional reform to reduce the powers of the 
European Commission. 
  "The status of the Commission as de facto exempt from any 
answerability" (in theory the European Parliament can censure 
it, but it has never seriously considered such a move) "is 
outdated, it is dead, it is no longer tolerated by the public," 
French European Affairs Minister Alain Lamassoure told 
journalists on Monday 13 June. Speaking on the occasion of the 
meeting of the Twelve's Council of Ministers, Mr. Lamassoure 
explained that he did not mean to have the slate wiped clean, 
that there was much to preserve in the way the Community works, 
including institutionally, but that the current system had 
become unbearable, that it was obsolete, and that -- "a true 
innovation" -- the Commission must be made answerable both to 
the Council of Ministers and the European Parliament. 
  This would not be the only reform, and the Commission's 
powers would be reduced even further. The French have been 
thinking of establishing, through the Council of Ministers, 
another authority which would be in charge of the Union's common 
foreign and security policy and would be headed by a personality 
with real powers and a clear brief. According to Mr. 
Lamassoure, the new treaty to be developed in 1996 as a 
replacement for the one devised in Maastricht should be 
subjected to a new referendum. "Only a referendum can alter 
what the people have instituted by means of a referendum; the 
idea is self-evident." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

