<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Congress Visit Denied </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Congress Visit Denied </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1906114994 Vienna DER STANDARD in German 18-19 Jun 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> AU1906114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DER STANDARD </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "cs": "Attacks Before the FPOe Congress"] </F>
  [Text] Vienna/Linz -- Just in time before the beginning of 
the Freedom Party of Austria [FPOe] congress, with which Joerg 
Haider wants to take the offensive again, new accusations 
against the FPOe chairman were disseminated on Friday [17 June]. 
Social Democratic Party of Austria [SPOe] Federal Manager Josef 
Cap quoted from an article in the FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU which 
accuses Haider of contacts with a group that is classified as 
right-wing extremist in the FRG. 
  U.S. Congressman Robert Torricelli -- the Democratic 
representative from New Jersey is the chairman of the 
Subcommittee on Western Hemisphere Affairs of the House Foreign 
Affairs Committee and involved in human rights issues -- has 
warned his 434 colleagues in the House of Representatives 
against meeting with FPOe Chairman Joerg Haider. In a 
memorandum Torricelli pointed out that Haider had praised the 
employment policy of the Third Reich. He should "not be honored 
by a visit to Congress." 
  Haider did not comment on this matter. FPOe officials are 
surprised that a visit to Congress is supposed to be prevented, 
which Haider neither intended nor had asked for. Rather, his 
visit to the United States next week is aimed at meeting 
Austrians living abroad in New York and talks with U.S. foreign 
policy experts about a potential Austrian membership in NATO. 
  This goal of the FPOe is to become both the topic of the 
party congress and the central issue in the election campaign, 
FPOe Secretary General Karl-Heinz Grasser told DER STANDARD. 
The congress, at which Haider wants to propose one or two new 
deputies, should also engage "a bit in coming to terms with the 
past." He will mention Erwin Hirnschall's "behavior that was 
damaging to the party." Hirnschall had rejected Haider's offer 
to present his arguments in favor of EU membership during 
Haider's own appearances and had, instead, criticized the party 
line in the "Press Hour" television program. 

</TEXT>

