<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Denies Accusation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Juppe Denies Accusation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706193394 Paris Radio France International in French 1830 
GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Belgian newspaper LE SOIR wrote this morning 
that President Habyarimana's aircraft might have been shot down 
on 6 April by two French soldiers wearing Belgian uniforms and 
acting on behalf of Hutu extremists. Belgian officials 
immediately said that this possibility had been rejected by 
their investigation committee. French Foreign Minister Alain 
Juppe, currently visiting Abidjan, brushed aside these 
accusations: 
  [Begin Juppe recording] From what I gather, the author used 
the conditional tense in his article. He reports allegations 
according to which the French were wearing Belgian uniforms, and 
so forth. I shall not expand further. According to my 
information this seems to be pure fabrication. I have no more 
comments to make. An investigation under the aegis of the UN 
secretary-general is currently underway to establish the truth. 
All these rumors are obviously baseless. I regret that such 
accusations are being made using the conditional tense. Either 
one is certain of the facts, and has evidence or one keeps 
quiet. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

